    {
      "id": "65806952_c253434a",
      "file_path": "feature-state-management/src/main/java/org/onap/policy/drools/statemanagement/RepositoryAudit.java",
      "patchset_number": 4,
      "line": 90,
      "message": "Shouldn't the pattern be: \"repository[0-9]*\\\\.audit\\\\.id\" ?\n\nThe '*' allows no digits, so the current properties still work, and the '.' character in a pattern ordinarily matches any character, so it needs to be escaped. One additional problem: this pattern also matches \"repository0.audit.id\", \"repository00.audit.id\", and \"repository007.audit.id\", none of which will work correctly. You could use the pattern I suggested above, and add an additional check to ensure it doesn't start with \"repository0\".",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 743,
        "name": "Ralph Straubs",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "rs8887@att.com",
        "username": "rs8887"
      },
      "updated": "2019-11-07 09:49:09.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": null,
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "id": "791c2a09_4d600fd5",
      "file_path": "feature-state-management/src/main/java/org/onap/policy/drools/statemanagement/RepositoryAudit.java",
      "patchset_number": 4,
      "line": 136,
      "message": "I think it is best if you don't break out of the loop, so an incompletely-provisioned index doesn't cause the loop to terminate prematurely. How about:\n\nif (data.isActive) {\n  runAudit(data);\n}",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 743,
        "name": "Ralph Straubs",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "rs8887@att.com",
        "username": "rs8887"
      },
      "updated": "2019-11-07 09:49:09.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": null,
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "5d739d81_c64b78a3",
      "file_path": "feature-state-management/src/main/java/org/onap/policy/drools/statemanagement/RepositoryAudit.java",
      "patchset_number": 4,
      "line": 90,
      "message": "good point - how about this:\n  repository[1-9][0-9]*\\\\.audit\\\\.id\n\nor could get more specific and limit the number of digits to two:\n  repository[1-9][0-9]?\\\\.audit\\\\.id",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 811,
        "name": "Jim Hahn",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "jrh3@att.com",
        "username": "jrh3"
      },
      "updated": "2019-11-07 13:55:09.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "65806952_c253434a",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "id": "16fa37ed_aab2edf3",
      "file_path": "feature-state-management/src/main/java/org/onap/policy/drools/statemanagement/RepositoryAudit.java",
      "patchset_number": 4,
      "line": 90,
      "message": "We also want to match the string 'repository.audit.id', which corresponds to index 0 (note that it is treated differently in 'InvokeData.getProperty(...)'). The easiest approach seems to be to use the following test:\n\ncurrName.matches(\"repository[0-9]*\\\\.audit\\\\.id\") && !currName.startsWith(\"resource0\")\n\nYou could also use a more complex pattern in 'matches' to get the same result.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 743,
        "name": "Ralph Straubs",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "rs8887@att.com",
        "username": "rs8887"
      },
      "updated": "2019-11-07 14:21:39.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "5d739d81_c64b78a3",
      "unresolved": true
    },
